05705nam a22007095i 9780813562384DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2013    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135623847 a10.36019/97808135623842doi  a(DE-B1597)530042  a(OCoLC)862746626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aMazzagetti, Dominick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aCharles Lee :bSelf Before Country /cDominick Mazzagetti. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b1 map, 1 illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRivergate Regionals Collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Fateful Choice -- t2. Lee's "American Expedition" -- t3. Lee's European Experience -- t4. Personality and Political Philosophy -- t5. A "Love Affair" with America -- t6. Foreign Officers in Service to America -- t7. America's Soldier -- t8. Rejoining Washington -- t9. Captivity, Betrayal, Exchange -- t10. Monmouth -- t11. Court-Martial -- t12. Bitterness, Despair, and Death -- tEpilogue: A Man Without a Country -- tAppendix A. James Wilkinson, Memoirs of My Own Times (1816): The Capture of Charles Lee -- tAppendix B. "Mr. Lee's Plan-March 29, 1777" -- tAppendix C. Washington and Lee's Battlefield Confrontation -- tAppendix D. Shades of Monmouth -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDominick Mazzagetti presents an engaging account of the life of Charles Lee, the forgotten man of the American Revolution. History has not been kind to Lee-for good reason. In this compelling biography, Mazzagetti compares Lee's life and attributes to those of George Washington and offers significant observations omitted from previous Lee biographies, including extensive correspondence with British officers in 1777 that reflects Lee's abandonment of the Patriots' cause. Lee, a British officer, a veteran of the French and Indian War, and a critic of King George III, arrived in New York City in 1773 with an ego that knew no bounds and tolerated no rivals.  A highly visible and newsworthy personality, he quickly took up the American cause and encouraged rebellion. As a result of this advocacy and his military skills, Lee was granted a commission as a major general in the Continental Army and soon became second-in-command to George Washington. He helped organize the defense of Boston, designed defenses for New York City, and commanded the force that repelled the British attack on Charleston. Upon his return to New York in 1776, Lee was considered by some leaders of the Revolution to be an alternative to George Washington, who was in full retreat from British forces. Lee's capture by the British in December 1776 put an end to that possibility. Lee's subsequent release in a prisoner exchange in 1778 and return to an American command led to a dramatic confrontation with Washington on the battlefield at Monmouth, New Jersey, in June 1778. Washington chastised Lee publicly for ordering an unnecessary retreat. Lee suffered the ignominy of a court-martial conviction for this blunder and spent the remaining years to his death in 1782 attacking Washington. Although few doubted Lee's loyalty at the time, his actions at Monmouth fueled speculation that he switched sides during his imprisonment. A discovery years after his death completed Lee's tale. In 1862, a researcher discovered "Mr. Lee's Plan," a detailed strategy for the defeat of the American rebels delivered to British General William Howe while Lee was held in captivity. This discovery sealed Lee's historical record and ended all further discussion of his contributions to the American Revolution. Today, few people even realize that Fort Lee, on the New Jersey side of the George Washington Bridge, was named in his honor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813562384423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813562384.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG